Here's an implementation using a HashSet in Java for finding common elements in two arrays with the best time complexity of O(n + m).

```java
import java.util.HashSet;
import java.util.Set;

public class Main {
    public static int[] findCommonElements(int[] arr1, int[] arr2) {
        Set<Integer> set1 = new HashSet<>();
        Set<Integer> set2 = new HashSet<>();

        // Add elements from arr1 to set1
        for (int num : arr1) {
            set1.add(num);
        }

        // Add elements from arr2 to set2
        for (int num : arr2) {
            set2.add(num);
        }

        // Find common elements using set intersection
        set2.retainAll(set1);

        // Convert the common elements back to an array
        int[] commonElements = new int[set2.size()];
        int i = 0;
        for (int num : set2) {
            commonElements[i++] = num;
        }

        return commonElements;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr1 = {1, 2, 2, 3, 4, 5};
        int[] arr2 = {2, 2, 4, 6, 7};

        int[] commonElements = findCommonElements(arr1, arr2);
        for (int num : commonElements) {
            System.out.println(num);
        }
    }
}
```

This implementation has a time complexity of O(n + m), where n is the number of elements in arr1 and m is the number of elements in arr2. The reason for this is as follows:

1. Adding elements from arr1 to set1 takes O(n) time.
2. Adding elements from arr2 to set2 also takes O(m) time.
3. Finding common elements using set intersection takes O(min(n, m)) time, because set_intersection will remove elements not present in set1 from set2.

However, in the worst case scenario, when set_intersection is called with set2 containing all elements of set1 (hence containing min(n, m) elements), the time complexity would be O(n), due to the basic operations performed while adding elements and intersection between two sets.

